This works:

```
export type OptionalTuNullable&lt;O&gt; = {
  [K in keyof O]-?: undefined extends O[K] ? NonNullable&lt;O[K]&gt; | null : O[K];
};
```

So for instance:

```
type R = {
  a: string;
  b?: string;
  c?: string | null;
  d: string | undefined;
};

type A = OptionalTuNullable&lt;R&gt;;
// A: {
//     a: string;
//     b: string | null;
//     c: string | null;
//     d: string | null;
// }
```

Then, for the &quot;Pick&quot; part, you can just resort to the standard `Pick` type:

```
type B = Pick&lt;A, &quot;a&quot; | &quot;c&quot;&gt;;
// B: {
//   a: string;
//   c: string | null;
// }
```

Summing up, I think this would work for your use case:

```
type VuexPick&lt;T, K extends keyof T&gt; = Pick&lt;OptionalTuNullable&lt;T&gt;, K&gt;

type C = VuexPick&lt;R, &#39;c&#39;&gt;
// C: {
//   c: string | null;
// }

```

Your type `B` gets resolved to this:
```
type B = {
  p1: string extends undefined ? null : string
  p2: string | undefined extends undefined ? null : string | undefined
};
```
`string | undefined` as supertype does not extend `undefined`, it is the other way around. So you end up with this type:
```
type B = {
    p1: string;
    p2: string;
}
```
You could instead create a `UndefinedToNull` type, which causes a [distributive conditional type][2] to be applied, as `T` is a [naked type parameter][3] now.
```
type VuexPick2&lt;T, K extends keyof T&gt; = {
  [P in K]-?: UndefinedToNull&lt;T[P]&gt;;
};

type UndefinedToNull&lt;T&gt; = T extends undefined ? null : T

type B2 = VuexPick2&lt;A, &quot;p1&quot; | &quot;p2&quot;&gt;; // type B2 = { p1: string; p2: string | null;}
```
E.g. type `UndefinedToNull&lt;string | undefined&gt;` is the same as `B4`:
```
type B4 = 
| (string extends undefined ? null: string) 
| (undefined extends undefined ? null: undefined) // type B4 = string | null
```

[Playground][4]


  [1]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-2-8.html#improved-control-over-mapped-type-modifiers
  [2]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-2-8.html#distributive-conditional-types
  [3]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51651499/typescript-what-is-a-naked-type-parameter
  [4]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/?ssl=26&amp;ssc=7&amp;pln=26&amp;pc=8#-G5-B5PRhKcaQylVGIdInCAAs8QAFHSKGDNsVGdDqrUjOolABKcZcoW-flbEpXOVwuq4WVUiUoIA

